[1
Date: Sat, 23 Mar 2002
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Cnews, 22 Mar 22, 2002 [edited
<http://www.canoe.ca/WorldTicker/CANOE-wire.Japan-Mad-Cow.html>


Japan steps up battle against mad cow [disease; expands testing of
sheep, goats
-----------------------------------------------------
Japan stepped up its battle against mad cow disease Friday with
expanded plans to screen the country's sheep and goats for scrapie, a
sickness linked to the fatal, brain-wasting disease in cattle. Scrapie
poses no direct threat to people, but about one million cattle in
Britain are believed to have contracted mad cow disease after eating
feed made from the carcasses of sheep infected with scrapie. [It has
been proven that they were infected through the feed, but not that the
infecting agent was the scrapie prion. - Mod.JW

Eating beef from cattle infected with mad cow disease is thought to
trigger a fatal human variant of the illness. As an extra precaution,
the Health Ministry said it would start testing sheep and goats 12
months of age and older for the disease, though no timetable has been
set yet, spokesman Hideshi Michino said. Currently, the ministry tests
sheep and goats 18 months of age and older.

Asia's first case of mad cow disease was detected on a Japanese farm
last September [2001. A month later, the government began screening
all beef bound for human consumption, amid widespread public concern
over the meat's safety.

Agriculture Ministry spokesman Seiya Tanaka said Friday that Japanese
beef is now its safest since those sweeps began, with nearly all beef
products made before the checks now off the market.

A total of 3 cases of mad cow disease, or bovine spongiform
encephalopathy, have been confirmed in Japan. There have been no new
cases so far this year [2002.

