[2
Date: Sat, 23 Mar 2002
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Food Standards Agency News Centre press release, 21 Mar 2002
[edited
<http://www.food.gov.uk/news/pressreleases/52581>


Spinal cord found in imported Polish beef
-----------------------------------------
Spinal cord has been found in 2 consignments of beef imported from
Poland into the UK. Bovine spinal cord is the part of the animal most
likely to contain BSE infectivity and is therefore classified as
specified risk material(SRM).

Beef from Poland entering the European Union (EU) must meet EU
standards, including the removal of SRM immediately after slaughter,
before the beef is
exported.

The first discovery was made on Mon 18 Mar 2002 in one forequarter out
of 268 quarters of beef being unloaded at Eastbourne. The beef was
imported from Poland. On Tue 19 Mar 2002, a second consignment of 238
beef quarters from a second meat plant in Poland being unloaded at
Eastbourne was also found to contain one quarter-carcass with spinal
cord still attached. The beef came from Bialystok, Poland.

Imports of meat from Poland are subject to EU controls, and have to
satisfy, among other requirements, EU controls on SRM, which require
that spinal cord be removed in the slaughterhouse of origin. Beef
imports to the UK from Poland, for the 12 months to 30 Nov 2001, were
47 tons, which is equivalent to 0.005% of UK beef consumption
(currently about 910 000 tons).

These finds of SRM in imported beef are the 25th and 26th instances
since 1 Jan 2001. They are the first ones to involve carcass beef from
a non-EU country.

Food Standards Agency Veterinary Director Debby Reynolds, said: "Any
find of SRM is illegal and a serious matter. There is no risk to
public health, as the affected meat has been removed from the food
chain. I am grateful that the Meat Hygiene Service took prompt action
to detain and destroy these 2 pieces of meat. The finds have also been
notified to the veterinary authorities in Poland, which have taken
swift action. Both Polish plants have had their authorization to
export beef suspended, and the Polish authorities are conducting an
urgent review of controls in those plants.

